{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01DiAwyoWGkZ1EpiyYv48Ftt","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→package org.quarkus.samples.petclinic.owner;\n     2→\n     3→import jakarta.ws.rs.ext.ParamConverter;\n     4→import jakarta.ws.rs.ext.ParamConverterProvider;\n     5→import jakarta.ws.rs.ext.Provider;\n     6→\n     7→import java.lang.annotation.Annotation;\n     8→import java.lang.reflect.Type;\n     9→import java.time.LocalDate;\n    10→\n    11→@Provider\n    12→public class LocalDateParamConverterProvider implements ParamConverterProvider {\n    13→\n    14→    @Override\n    15→    public <T> ParamConverter<T> getConverter(Class<T> rawType, Type genericType,\n    16→                                              Annotation[] annotations) {\n    17→        if (rawType.equals(LocalDate.class))\n    18→            return (ParamConverter<T>) new LocalDateConverter();\n    19→        return null;\n    20→    }\n    21→\n    22→}\n    23→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"7877d114-a8cd-4b86-860b-21ca41dfcbd5","uuid":"70464405-4ad3-4cae-b364-27aa87b54b23"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01V79Z5A6652dowHQdQ3bKwL","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→package org.quarkus.samples.petclinic.owner;\n     2→\n     3→import jakarta.ws.rs.ext.ParamConverter;\n     4→\n     5→import java.time.LocalDate;\n     6→\n     7→public class LocalDateConverter implements ParamConverter<LocalDate> {\n     8→\n     9→    @Override\n    10→    public LocalDate fromString(String value) {\n    11→        if (\"\".equals(value.trim()))\n    12→            return null;\n    13→        return LocalDate.parse(value);\n    14→    }\n    15→\n    16→    @Override\n    17→    public String toString(LocalDate value) {\n    18→        if (value == null)\n    19→            return null;\n    20→        return value.toString();\n    21→    }\n    22→\n    23→}\n    24→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"7877d114-a8cd-4b86-860b-21ca41dfcbd5","uuid":"b857dce5-18b7-4fc0-b755-0295e51f3e89"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_016iFKEpyVYC6Cr9zqE7cM6m","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→package org.quarkus.samples.petclinic.owner;\n     2→\n     3→import java.util.Comparator;\n     4→\n     5→import org.quarkus.samples.petclinic.visit.Visit;\n     6→\n     7→public class VisitComparator implements Comparator<Visit> {\n     8→\n     9→    @Override\n    10→    public int compare(Visit o1, Visit o2) {\n    11→        return o1.date.compareTo(o2.date);\n    12→    }\n    13→    \n    14→}\n    15→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"7877d114-a8cd-4b86-860b-21ca41dfcbd5","uuid":"88f2aee7-d17d-4fe3-be5b-c99210b2a8cd"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01C1eRX58rDURi5jz4NFyWVm","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→package org.quarkus.samples.petclinic.vet;\n     2→\n     3→import java.util.ArrayList;\n     4→import java.util.Collections;\n     5→import java.util.HashSet;\n     6→import java.util.List;\n     7→import java.util.Set;\n     8→\n     9→import jakarta.persistence.Entity;\n    10→import jakarta.persistence.FetchType;\n    11→import jakarta.persistence.JoinColumn;\n    12→import jakarta.persistence.JoinTable;\n    13→import jakarta.persistence.ManyToMany;\n    14→import jakarta.persistence.Table;\n    15→import org.quarkus.samples.petclinic.model.Person;\n    16→\n    17→@Entity\n    18→@Table(name = \"vets\")\n    19→public class Vet extends Person {\n    20→    \n    21→    @ManyToMany(fetch = FetchType.EAGER)\n    22→\t@JoinTable(name = \"vet_specialties\", joinColumns = @JoinColumn(name = \"vet_id\"),\n    23→\t\t\tinverseJoinColumns = @JoinColumn(name = \"specialty_id\"))\n    24→\tpublic Set<Specialty> specialties;\n    25→\n    26→\tprotected Set<Specialty> getSpecialtiesInternal() {\n    27→\t\tif (this.specialties == null) {\n    28→\t\t\tthis.specialties = new HashSet<>();\n    29→\t\t}\n    30→\t\treturn this.specialties;\n    31→\t}\n    32→\n    33→\tpublic List<Specialty> getSpecialties() {\n    34→\t\tList<Specialty> sortedSpecs = new ArrayList<>(getSpecialtiesInternal());\n    35→\t\tCollections.sort(sortedSpecs, new SpecialityComparator());\n    36→\t\treturn Collections.unmodifiableList(sortedSpecs);\n    37→\t}\n    38→\n    39→\tpublic int getNrOfSpecialties() {\n    40→\t\treturn getSpecialtiesInternal().size();\n    41→\t}\n    42→\n    43→\tpublic void addSpecialty(Specialty specialty) {\n    44→\t\tgetSpecialtiesInternal().add(specialty);\n    45→\t}\n    46→\n    47→\t@Override\n    48→\tpublic String toString() {\n    49→\t\treturn super.toString() + \" Vet [specialties=\" + specialties + \"]\";\n    50→\t}\n    51→\n    52→\t\n    53→\n    54→}\n    55→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"7877d114-a8cd-4b86-860b-21ca41dfcbd5","uuid":"23339853-ba44-4825-a218-306943cd8b9c"}
